 model of the lunar tide, chopping the continental shelf around the British Isles into roughly 1000 square cells. Flather estimated that the total average power entering this region is 215 GW. According to his model, 180 GW enters the gap between France and Ireland. From Northern Ireland round to Shetland, the incoming power is 49 GW. Between Shetland and Norway there is a net loss of 5 GW. As shown in figure G.4, Cartwright et al. (1980) found experimentally that the average power transmission was 60 GW between Malin Head (Ireland) and Flor\xF8 (Norway) and 190 GW between Valentia (Ireland) and the Brittany coast near Ouessant. The power entering the Irish Sea was found to be 45 GW, and entering the North Sea via the Dover Straits, 16.7 GW."),mdx("p",null,mdx("img",e({parentName:"p"},{src:"/img/without-hot-air/figure301.gif",alt:null}))),mdx("span",{class:"figurenumber"},"Figure G.4.")," Average tidal powers measured by Cartwright et al. (1980).",mdx("h3",e({},{id:"the-power-of-tidal-waves"}),"The power of tidal waves"),mdx("p",null,"This section, which can safely be skipped, provides more details behind the formula for tidal power used in the previous section. I\u2019m going to go into this model of tidal power in some detail because most of the official estimates of the UK tidal resource have been based on a model that I believe is incorrect."),mdx("p",null,"Figure G.2 shows a model for a tidal wave travelling across relatively shallow water. This model is intended as a cartoon, for example, of tidal crests moving up the English channel or down the North Sea. It\u2019s important to distinguish the speed ",mdx("em",{parentName:"p"},"U")," at which the water itself moves (which might be about 1 mile per hour) from the speed v at which the high tide moves, which is typically 100 or 200 miles per hour."),mdx("p",null,"The water has depth ",mdx("em",{parentName:"p"},"d"),". Crests and troughs of water are injected from the left hand side by the 12-hourly ocean tides. 